		<item>
		<title>Friction and your Myers-Briggs type</title>
		<link>http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/friction-and-your-myers-briggs-type/</link>
		<comments>http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/friction-and-your-myers-briggs-type/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 24 Jul 2012 12:00:05 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Dirk]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Myers-Briggs]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[understanding]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://facio.com/?p=353</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>As I&#8217;ve become increasingly well-versed in the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator(R) over the past couple of years, I keep discovering it is like an onion: the deeper you get the more layers there are. The big downside with the MBTI and &#8230; <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/friction-and-your-myers-briggs-type/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a></p><p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/friction-and-your-myers-briggs-type/">Friction and your Myers-Briggs type</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>As I&#8217;ve become increasingly well-versed in the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator(R) over the past couple of years, I keep discovering it is like an onion: the deeper you get the more layers there are. The big downside with the MBTI and the general Myers-Briggs style preference frameworks is the relative complexity. The presentation of one&#8217;s type in 16 categories using obtuse letters can be arcane for many users. The upside is, for serious analysis and study, it is much deeper than the preponderance of other tools out there. That&#8217;s why there are so many layers to keep exploring.</p>
<p>In studying my own type and behaviour, I intuitively felt there were inherent frictions between my facets, frictions that I suspected were not unique to me but common to many people of particular types. Talking about this over dinner with my friend Ann, an MBTI Master Practitioner, she acknowledged that what I was intuiting was a very real part of type dynamics. This is useful enough to provide interesting personal insights that I want to share it here.</p>
<p>For the purpose of this analysis, we are looking at how one&#8217;s Attitudes (E-I) relate to their Judging Functions (T-F) and how one&#8217;s Perceiving Functions (S-N) relate to their Lifestyle (J-P). Half of these pairing represent what I will call a &#8220;natural alignment&#8221; that lend themselves to a more comfortable natural functioning and the other half represent what I will call a &#8220;natural conflict&#8221;, providing friction for a person going through their life. Those labels are just convenient for this short post and are not suggested as formal labels to identify these characteristics beyond this.</p>
<table style="margin: 0px 20px 20px 0; float: left; border: 1px solid #303030; padding: 20px;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 20px;" colspan="4">Naturally Aligned Pairs</td>
</tr>
<tr style="font-size: 32px; font-weight: bold;">
<td class="mbti-type-pair">E-F</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">I-T</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">S-J</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">N-P</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>E-F (Extraversion-Feeling) &#8211; getting your energy from other people, and making first judgements in people-centered ways</p>
<p>I-T (Introversion-Thinking) &#8211; getting your energy from inside yourself, and making first judgements in objective ways</p>
<p>S-J (Sensing-Judging) &#8211; perceiving the world in the moment through your senses, and making in-the-moment decisions and moving on to the next thing</p>
<p>N-P (iNtuition-Perceiving) &#8211; perceiving the world of ideas through your mind, and being compelled to delay decisions to keep options open</p>
<p>Those come together so naturally it may not be immediately apparent those short explanations are summarizing BOTH of the pairs they represent. The good news for those with strong alignment is they likely fit into the expectations of others better, and suffer less internal friction thanks to not naturally being compelled toward divergent ways of functioning. Now, look at the next list:</p>
<table style="margin: 0 20px 20px 0; float: left; border: 1px solid #303030; padding: 20px;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 20px;" colspan="4">Naturally Conflicting Pairs</td>
</tr>
<tr style="font-size: 32px; font-weight: bold;">
<td class="mbti-type-pair">E-T</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">I-F</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">S-P</td>
<td class="mbti-type-pair">N-J</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>E-T (Extraversion-Thinking) &#8211; getting your energy from other people, and making first judgments in objective ways</p>
<p>I-F (Introversion-Feeling) &#8211; getting your energy from inside yourself, and making first judgements in people-centered ways</p>
<p>S-P (Sensing-Perceiving) &#8211; perceiving the world in the moment through your senses, and being compelled to delay decisions to keep options open</p>
<p>N-J (iNtuition-Judging) &#8211; perceiving the world of ideas through your mind, and making in-the-moment decisions to close off one thing and move on to the next</p>
<p>See the contrast?</p>
<p>When your inherent preferences are thus conflicting, it is reflected in how others perceive you and how you manage yourself. For example, someone who is an E-T will seem friendly and gregarious, then will surprise you with their harsh criticism. Whereas, if an I -T were to criticize harshly you would be more likely to expect it based on other behavioural cues and natural assumptions. Or, an I-F is likely struggling inside of themselves, on one hand wanting their solitary time in order to be nurtured and replenished, while wanting to care for and deeply engage with someone else. The path forward is not simple, and gratifying either necessarily rubs the other one the wrong way. For people whose type has both pairs conflicting &#8211; ESTP, ENTJ, ISFP, INFJ &#8211; life and identity can seem particularly draining. Of course, on the flip side successful CEO&#8217;s are disproportionately ENTJs, and great artists are disproportionately ISFP&#8217;s. So while there may be a price to pay for that conflict, there are also successes and achievement borne from the trials of contradiction.</p>
<p>Of course, let us not forget that who and what we are is the product of many vectors, beyond our Myers-Briggs style preferences. So the impact of strong alignment or mis-alignment for each person can be significantly different. However, awareness of these dynamics can put us in better touch with ourselves, help us understand what is going on as we function and make decisions, and perhaps even better understand each other.</p>
<p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/friction-and-your-myers-briggs-type/">Friction and your Myers-Briggs type</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/friction-and-your-myers-briggs-type/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		</item>
		<item>
		<title>Hello, nice to meet you&#8230;</title>
		<link>http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/hello-nice-to-meet-you-2/</link>
		<comments>http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/hello-nice-to-meet-you-2/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 03 Jul 2012 12:00:06 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Dirk]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[understanding]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://facio.com/?p=340</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>While the Internet gives us wonderful tools to learn about people, how well are we really getting to know them? When I am introduced to someone new the first thing I do is Google them. I&#8217;m looking for their personal &#8230; <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/hello-nice-to-meet-you-2/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a></p><p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/hello-nice-to-meet-you-2/">Hello, nice to meet you&#8230;</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<figure class="alignleft" style="width: 300px;"><img class="size-medium wp-image-427" title="google-linkedin" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/google-linkedin-300x42.png" alt="" width="300" height="42" /><br />
<figcaption>While the Internet gives us wonderful tools to learn about people, how well are we really getting to know them?</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>When I am introduced to someone new the first thing I do is Google them. I&#8217;m looking for their personal website first and foremost, as well as their Twitter stream and LinkedIn page. I want to start to learn about this new person, to see connections and pathways from which we can engage with one another. Yet, even across all of those various services, I&#8217;m really getting very little. Most people don&#8217;t have personal websites. While some people are active Twitter users, far more are not. LinkedIn becomes the general &#8220;go-to&#8221; resource, but it is a remnant from our analog past: a resume with some recommendations stapled to it, now clumsily integrating information about the person&#8217;s &#8220;skills&#8221;. I&#8217;m learning little of value.</p>
<p>The richest way to explore someone is to meet them face-to-face. You can learn a lot through a simple conversation, that is not possible in any other way. But there is also much that is missed. To varying degrees we curate and prune ourselves when meeting others for the first time. Or, we end up focusing on topics or trains of thought that are &#8220;down to business&#8221; and do not end up giving much of a window into the individual. This is unfortunate. How much could we get out of our time with others if we understood them better? Not what college they went to or where they worked 10 years ago; I&#8217;m talking about who they really are, in ways that can expedite mutual understanding, productivity and value.</p>
<p>One of the many things we are trying to do with Facio is give each of us the raw materials to understand ourselves more clearly and completely, along with the ability to share that information as much or as little as we would like. Me, I&#8217;m the extreme person who is going to make all of their reports public. I want people to know exactly who they are dealing with: the positive as well as the negative. While that kind of transparency won&#8217;t be comfortable for everyone &#8211; and thus they can choose to share with just a few people or no one if they like &#8211; I have enjoyed exceptional success in my life via quickly sharing more information about myself that helps other people understand and deal with me better. It takes some courage to really go all the way with it, but it is a powerful thing. If this makes you uncomfortable, try sharing with just your family or very closest friends first. Even if you don&#8217;t want to take it any farther than that, you will almost certainly find that a greater depth of awareness and understanding is a good thing.</p>
<p>Who we are is not about our resume; it is about our personality, behaviours, motivations, preferences, skills and so much more. The better we understand ourselves and each other, the better our outcomes will increasingly become.</p>
<p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2012/07/hello-nice-to-meet-you-2/">Hello, nice to meet you&#8230;</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded>
